annotation.TEXT: A reference to ‘80s ads for Sure deodorant.
“Here come de judge” was a catchphrase originated by comedian Dewey “Pigmeat” Markham that became a recurring gag on the TV show Rowan & Martin’s Laugh-In.
Roger “Raj” Thomas was the third young man at the center of What’s Happening!!
Episode 501, Warrior of the Lost World, takes place in a post-apocalyptic wasteland.
Dr. (or Doc) Martens is a brand of footwear popular with everyone from police officers & mail carriers to skinheads & musicians. They are sturdy and not cheap.
Choreographer and dancer Deney Terrio hosted Dance Fever. He also taught John Travolta his famous disco moves for Saturday Night Fever.
The Ed Sullivan Show was a variety show hosted by entertainment columnist Ed Sullivan. It ran for 23 years.
The TV show Ripley’s Believe It or Not! aired from 1982-86 and was hosted by Jack Palance, who seemed to truly savor delivering the line “Believe it … or not.”
Conaway bounced back with a role as security officer Zack Allan on the late-‘90s sci-fi series Babylon 5.
King Friday XIII is the monarch of the “Neighborhood of Make-Believe,” the puppet kingdom on the children’s TV show Mister Rogers’ Neighborhood.
Chris Lemmon is an actor and author and the son of actor Jack Lemmon. Actress Heather Locklear is known for the TV series Dynasty, Melrose Place, and Spin City.
The retrograde sexism of the Gor novels is widely known; basically women are seen as mere possessions of men, to be owned, chained, and raped at will—and they love it.
Most of De Beers’ diamond mines are in Africa, and the company has sometimes been accused of exploiting its workers, most of whom are extremely poor.
A line from the Carpenters’ hit single “I Won’t Last a Day Without You.”
Fred Flintstone was the star of the animated TV show The Flintstones. Fred generally wore an orange and black tunic with a wide, tattered electric-blue necktie.
“Midnight at the Oasis” became a No. 6 hit single in 1974 for Maria Muldaur.
Dance Party USA was a TV dance show that aired from 1986-92 on the USA Network.
On The Simpsons episode “Bart’s Friend Falls in Love,” an ad for the Good Morning Burger promises 18 ounces of ground beef “soak[ed] in rich creamery butter.”
The title song on the Jethro Tull Aqualung album begins with an iconic power guitar riff.
A famous ‘80s ad campaign for Irish Spring soap used the slogan “Manly, yes, but I like it too”—referring to its traditionally masculine scent.
Susan Powter was an infomercial queen back in the early ‘90s, a workout guru whose motto was “Stop the Insanity!”
Throughout the early ‘90s, viewers of Live! with Regis and Kathie Lee were treated to detailed descriptions of Kathie Lee Gifford’s marriage and pregnancies.
Greg Norman was a top-ranked blond professional golfer from Australia in the ‘80s and ‘90s, nicknamed “The Great White Shark.”
In the early ‘90s, Keystone beer ran ads saying, “Wouldn’t it be great if …” followed by an extended fantasy riff, and ending with, “and they served beer? Really great beer, like Keystone …”
Actress Melanie Griffith is best known for her Golden Globe-winning performance in the film Working Girl.
A gin fizz is an alcoholic cocktail consisting of gin, lemon juice, sugar, and carbonated water, served in a highball glass with ice.
William Devane is best known for playing scheming Senator Greg Sumner on the primetime soap opera Knots Landing.
TGI Fridays is a nationwide restaurant chain known for its “antique clutter” decorating scheme. Mike Nelson was a waiter there when he began writing for MST3K.
A famous line from the pilot of the sitcom The Mary Tyler Moore Show, spoken by gruff newsman Lou Grant to Mary during a job interview.
Outlaw of Gor: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
The Forum was a personal growth seminar popular in California in the ‘80s, a successor to the EST movement of the ‘70s.
Comedian Pat Paulsen appeared on the Smothers Brothers, but he is best remembered for his six tongue-in-cheek campaigns for president.
The National Organization for Women is a 500,000-member feminist group in the U.S. that advocates on issues important to women.
The Lone Ranger’s sidekick was Tonto, played by Jay Silverheels on the TV show. (His horse was named Scout.)
The Prisoner is a British TV series about an ex-secret agent who is kept prisoner in a surreal village. It only aired for one season but earned a loyal cult following.
The song “Deep in the Heart of Texas” is performed with four distinct claps before the title phrase is sung.
A Sampo is a magical artifact in Finnish mythology that can take many forms and brings good luck; it featured heavily in Episode 422, The Day the Earth Froze.
From the song “Cruella de Vil,” featured in the Disney animated film One Hundred and One Dalmatians. Cruella de Vil is the fashion-obsessed villain of the movie.
“L’chaim” is a Jewish toast that means “to life” in Hebrew. A young Jewish couple’s engagement celebration is also called a l’chaim.
Cosmopolitan, or Cosmo, is a women’s magazine known for cover photos of cleavagey women and articles with titles like “10 Ways to Drive Your Man Wild in Bed.”
A Boy Scout Jamboree is a large gathering of Boy Scouts. There are various national and international Jamborees; the World Scout Jamboree is held every four years.
Camille Paglia and Susan Faludi are both authors who write on feminism, but their views are incompatible, and the two are not fond of each other.
Marlene Dietrich was a German-born actress who first made it big playing a cabaret singer in Der blaue Engel (The Blue Angel) before coming to Hollywood.
The Wall Street Journal is a daily newspaper with a business and financial focus.
After years of substance abuse issues, he infamously appeared on Celebrity Rehab in 2008.
During the early Christian era, the Romans executed some prisoners, including Christians, using animals: dogs, bears, boars, panthers, and, yes, lions.
With 18 major championships, Jack Nicklaus is considered the most accomplished pro golfer in history. He is also a respected golf course designer; many golf communities use his designs.
Windex is a brand of glass and hard surface cleaner.
Warlock: The Armageddon is a sequel to the horror flick Warlock, starring Julian Sands in the title role as the son of Satan.
Barney Rubble was Fred Flintstone’s best buddy on the TV series The Flintstones.
Mel Tormé was one of the 20th century’s most respected jazz vocalists, whose smooth, resonant voice earned him the nickname “The Velvet Fog.”
And let us know if we missed any references!
On the TV show The Rockford Files, Rockford famously offered his services for “$200 a day, plus expenses.”
Fred Dryer is a former NFL football star who went on to a modestly successful acting career, most famously as the lead on the police drama Hunter.
A common way to begin wedding ceremonies is with, “Dearly beloved, we are gathered here today …”
“Hi-yo, Silver, awaaay!” is the classic catchphrase of the Lone Ranger, a fictional renegade lawman played most famously by Clayton Moore. (Silver was his horse, BTW.)
A reference to Renaissance Faires and a callback to Episode 303, Pod People.
Martha Raye was a singer/actress famous as the Polident pitchwoman, but the writers were probably thinking of Norma Rae, a film about a woman trying to unionize her textile mill.
Pine-Sol is a line of household cleaning products made by Clorox. The original formulation contains pine oil (hence the name).
“Aw Du Peepo Abba in Da Woooaa” is the show-stopping song heard during the traumatizing kissing scene at the end of Warrior of the Lost World.
“Yes … But Is It Art?” is an infamous 60 Minutes piece from 1993 that harshly criticized the artists, art critics, and dealers who produce, promote, and sell modern art.
Little person actor Billy Barty appeared in more than 80 films and TV series during his lengthy career, including Episode 806, The Undead.
A lot of Freud’s theories seemed to revolve around the penis. In addition to penis envy, there was castration anxiety, the phallic stage, the phallic woman, and of course those cigars.
The USA Network is a basic cable network that was known for somewhat racy fare in the ‘90s, including La Femme Nikita and Silk Stalkings.
A line from the song “Wind Beneath My Wings,” which became a No. 1 single for Bette Midler in 1989, from the soundtrack for the film Beaches.
Crystal Light is a low-calorie drink mix, similar to Kool-Aid. Its ‘80s-era slogan declared: “I believe in Crystal Light ‘cause I believe in me!”
In the Dune novels by Frank Herbert, giant sandworms live under the surface of the desert planet Arrakis. Vibrations or bulges in the sand that indicate a sandworm are called wormsign.
Actress Adrienne Barbeau is known for the sitcom Maude and for several ‘80s horror movies, including The Fog and Swamp Thing.
Despite depictions in Western media, “Arabic ululations” are typically only performed by women and most often during times of celebration.
Doc Savage is a fictional bronze-haired, rock-muscled action-adventure hero originally published in pulp magazines in the ‘30s and ‘40s.
In that scene, Robert “The Paper Chase Guy” Ginty and Persis Khambatta kiss for a full 70 seconds.
Nell Carter was an actress and singer known for her hefty frame and resonant voice. She was most famous for the ‘80s sitcom Gimme a Break!
Pinky Tuscadero was a minor character on the TV series Happy Days. Pinky’s little sister was Leather Tuscadero.
Starlight Express is a stage musical by Andrew Lloyd Webber in which all the cast members are on roller skates.
Hart Bochner is best known for playing the sleazy Harry Ellis in the film Die Hard.
Mary Harris “Mother” Jones was a labor and community organizer who worked with the United Mine Workers union and brought attention to child labor in mines & textile mills.
“Flight of the Bumblebee” is a 1900 orchestral piece by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov notable for its speed and complexity.
Conaway then starred in the first three seasons of the TV sitcom Taxi before leaving the show, partially due to his drug use.
A line from the song “Black Velvet,” which was a No. 1 hit for singer Alannah Myles in 1990.
Thus ends the fully-annotated Outlaw of Gor.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Bishop’s Buffet was a chain of cafeteria-style restaurants in the Midwest. The last one closed in 2012.
In the ‘90s, Italian government was in turmoil due to corruption, massive debt, and the influence of organized crime. Controversial elections led to frequent power transfers.
David Letterman was a late-night talk show host known for his offbeat sense of humor. He retired in 2015.
Fisherman terms. “Big jacks” likely refers to crevalle jack, a large saltwater fish. “Silver spoon” is a type of lure often used to catch them.
Did we miss any references? Let us know in the comments!
Home Pride Butter Top Bread slices the top of each loaf and bakes in butter.
Sheila E. is a musician and actress who began as a drummer in Minneapolis rocker Prince’s band and later branched out into her own solo career.
A paraphrased line from the Sylvester Stallone film Cliffhanger: “Time to kill a mountain man.”
Now prepare yourself for…the fully-annotated Outlaw of Gor!
Possibly borrowed from the litany of tough-cop talk heard in the ABC police drama NYPD Blue.
On the TV show Star Trek, Dr. Leonard “Bones” McCoy uttered some variation on the phrase “He’s dead, Jim” about 20 times. It became a popular catchphrase.
“Baba” is a term of respect for elderly men in several Asian and African cultures.
The Pietà is a marble sculpture by Michelangelo that depicts the Virgin Mary holding the body of her son on her lap after his crucifixion.
Woody Allen was caught up in a scandal in 1992 around his relationship with Soon-Yi Previn, the adopted daughter of his long-term lover Mia Farrow.
Morgan Fairchild is an actress known for her glamorous TV roles in the ‘70s and ‘80s, including a star turn on Falcon Crest.
Bob Fosse was the choreographer and director behind some classic 20th-century musicals, including Cabaret and All That Jazz.
Henry Fonda also appeared in ads for other GAF products such as View-Master (along with a young Jodie Foster) in the ‘60s and ‘70s.
Faces of Death is a film depicting explicit scenes of death and violence, some faked and others quite real, culled from newsreels, wartime footage, and one fatal traffic accident.
Sir Chomps-a-Lot was a line of canned, bite-size ravioli made by Chef Boyardee that was marketed heavily to children in the ‘80s and ‘90s.
Michael J. Fox got his start playing conservative teen Alex Keaton on the TV series Family Ties and then starred in the wildly popular Back to the Future films in the ‘80s.
A recurring line from the Mel Brooks film History of the World, Part I. Brooks, as King Louis XVI of France, would assert smugly to the camera, “It’s good to be the king.”
On The Flintstones, Fred Flintstone worked in a rock quarry; his boss was Mr. Slate.
A riff on a line from mid-‘90s TV ads for the Minnesota School of Bartending.
Pert Plus is a brand of shampoo plus conditioner, a variation on the original Pert shampoo. “Wash & go with Pert” was an ad jingle for the brand in the ‘80s.
The notorious flop Ishtar is a movie about two lounge singers who get mixed up in a CIA plot in Morocco. There is a lengthy sequence in which the pair get lost in the desert.
Eight-track tapes were the first portable and durable format for recorded music in cars. They were replaced by cassettes in the mid-‘70s.
TV’s Bloopers & Practical Jokes is a fairly self-explanatory show that aired periodically from 1984-2007; it was revived for syndication in 2012.
Queen Elizabeth a.k.a. the Queen Mother, mom to current Queen Elizabeth II, died at the age of 101, beloved by all for her enormous hats and fondness for gin.
Probably an imitation of the gratingly cheerful speaking style of Ned Flanders, Homer Simpson’s much-loathed next-door neighbor on The Simpsons.
To make “Ed” appear to talk, his trainer initially put a piece of nylon thread in his mouth, but Bamboo Harvester was so bright he quickly learned to move his lips on cue.
Pittsburgh, PA, was historically known for its steel industry, but its economy is now largely based on healthcare, tech, and finance.
A line from the film Monty Python and the Holy Grail, in which a protesting elderly relative tries to stop John Cleese from dumping him on the plague cart.
In the iconic “mockumentary” This Is Spinal Tap, the lead guitarist’s girlfriend Jeanine, all teased blond hair and spandex, joins the band on tour and upsets their dynamic to no end.
Dwayne Nelson and Freddy “Rerun” Stubbs were two of the three central teenage boys in the sitcom What’s Happening!!
An oft-quoted lyric from the song “Won’t Get Fooled Again” by The Who—a classic rock radio standard and a concert warhorse for the band.
Actress Jane Russell got her start in The Outlaw, a famous still from which showed her tumbled in a pile of hay, with her décolletage on abundant display.
In the rock opera Jesus Christ Superstar, the song “What’s the Buzz?” begins with, and often repeats, the line “What’s the buzz, tell me what’s a-happening.”
Intolerance is a silent film that weaves together storylines from different time periods, including one in ancient Babylonia, which features mammoth, ridiculously lavish sets.
Probably a riff on the Amana brand of refrigerators. You take off a fridge door before leaving it out for trash pickup to prevent pets or children from getting trapped inside.
Comedian Morty Gunty appeared on many TV shows in the ‘50s, ‘60s, and ‘70s.
The New York Times Book Review is an influential weekly book review supplement to The New York Times newspaper, published since 1896.
Sweeps week refers to the week in which the Nielsen company tallies TV viewership data. Networks air new episodes and specials to attract viewers during this period.
Bronk was a TV crime drama starring Jack Palance as Detective Lieutenant Alex Bronkov. It ran for only one season, from 1975-76.
Menahem Golan and Yoram Globus produced some of the cheesiest films of the ‘80s, including Episode 516, Alien From L.A.
In the highly successful film comedy City Slickers, Jack Palance said to the (much shorter) Billy Crystal: “I crap bigger than you.”
Joan Fontaine and her sister Olivia de Havilland were Golden Age Hollywood actresses who feuded with each other for years.
Actress Wendie Jo Sperber played the exuberantly romantic Amy Cassidy in Bosom Buddies.
“Keep on Truckin’” is a one-page comic by R. Crumb from 1968 that became an iconic symbol of defiance and optimism for the hippie counterculture, much to Crumb’s chagrin.
Comedian and actor Chevy Chase hosted a late night talk show in 1993 that was cancelled after four weeks; it is considered one of the most spectacular failures in TV.
Impress your friends by learning the meaning behind every reference, no matter how obscure.
Miller’s Crossing is a Coen brothers black comedy about a war between rival gangsters during Prohibition.
Short Round (played by Vietnamese actor Jonathan Ke Quan) was Indiana Jones’ 11-year-old sidekick in the film Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom.
Honey, I Shrunk the Kids is a family comedy starring Rick Moranis as a bumbling inventor who accidentally shrinks his children to less than an inch. Hijinks ensue.
In 1993, the year this episode first aired, actor Ted Danson performed an ill-advised blackface comedy routine at the roast of his then-girlfriend, Whoopi Goldberg.
Supertramp is a British rock band known for imaginative storytelling and lead singer Roger Hodgson’s extraordinary vocal range.
A reference to the song “The Phony King of England” in the Disney animated movie Robin Hood.
The Playboy bunny logo is printed on scented cardboard air fresheners destined for the rear-view mirrors of cars. Camaros, for example.
Newsies is a movie musical flop about a newsboys’ strike in 1899. Swing Kids is a film about teens in 1939 Germany who try to mix dancing with fascism; it got mixed reviews.
This phrase is used repeatedly in the first chapter of Dune and in Paul’s dream sequence in the film. “The long version” may be a reference to the extended TV version of the film.
There are various types of vacuum pump devices that can be used to treat erectile dysfunction in men.
“The Wizard of Id” is a comic strip set in the medieval kingdom of Id; people who offend the king often wind up chained to the wall in his dungeon.
Jiffy Pop popcorn comes in an aluminum foil pan with a spiral foil lid. As the pan is heated, the kernels pop and expand the lid into a bulbous container.
A line from the Roger Whittaker song “I Don’t Believe In ‘If’ Anymore,” which was a hit single in 1970 and 1975.
When Palance received his Best Supporting Actor Academy Award for City Slickers, from Oscar host Billy Crystal, he revised the line to: “Billy Crystal … I crap bigger than him.”
Albino blues/jazz/experimental musician Edgar Winter’s best-known song is “Frankenstein,” which hit number one in 1973.
The song’s actual title is “Let Me in Your Life,” performed by Chrystina Myers.
An old ad jingle for Keebler cookies.
“Dreamer” was a hit single off Supertramp’s 1974 album Crime of the Century.
Dance belts aren’t actually belts. They’re support garments for the genitals.
Probably a reference to Pope Paschal II, who reigned from 1099-1118 B.C.E and continued the Crusades begun by his predecessor, Urban II.
Actually, Outlaw was filmed in Namibia and South Africa.
Nicknamed “The Great One,” Wayne Gretzky played 20 seasons for four teams in the NHL.
The Osmonds were a singing group of Mormon brothers who hit it big in the ‘70s with squeaky-clean pop songs like “Sweet and Innocent” and “Puppy Love.”
In the “Science Fiction Sketch” on Monty Python’s Flying Circus, Earth is invaded by giant, tennis-playing blancmanges from the planet Skyron who are plotting to win Wimbledon.
Dove Bars are ice cream bars created in 1956 by a Greek immigrant from Chicago. They weren’t introduced nationally until Mars Inc. bought them in 1985.
The Marquess of Queensberry rules are the code upon which modern boxing is based. They were named after boxing enthusiast John Douglas, 9th Marquess of Queensberry.
Judy and Audrey Landers were sibling actresses famous for their dual 1983 spread in Playboy, although they also appeared in many films and TV shows.
Tupperware is a brand of plastic storage containers traditionally sold at “Tupperware parties,” in which a sales rep pitches to a group of women gathered at someone’s home.
A paraphrase of the America song “A Horse With No Name.”
In 1917 Lawrence was captured, beaten, and sexually abused by the Ottoman military. He admitted to being a masochist, and later in life paid a fellow soldier to beat him.
Lisa Hartman Black got her start on Knots Landing. When her character was killed off, fans freaked, so they brought her back as a different, lookalike character.
Richard Chamberlain became a teen heartthrob on the TV show Dr. Kildare and later appeared in the miniseries Shōgun and The Thorn Birds.
Chevy Camaros have gained a reputation as the ride of choice for blue-collar men and the women who love them.
“Missed me, missed me, now you gotta kiss me” is a durable schoolyard taunt that has been passed down through many generations, along with “Liar, liar, pants on fire.”
The Amish are a conservative Christian sect of Swiss-German descent known for their rejection of much modern technology, including electricity and cars.
Conaway died three years later of pneumonia and encephalopathy, exacerbated by his addictions.
A line from Devo’s hit single “Whip It.”
Fame is a film/TV show/stage musical/etc. about the lives and loves of a plucky group of students attending the New York High School of Performing Arts.
A reference to the lovely and haunting theme song from Episode 512, Mitchell, sung when Mitchell is in bed with hooker/girlfriend Linda Evans.
Red Roof Inn is a chain of economy hotels, mostly in the American Midwest, South, and East.
The use of nets in commercial tuna fishing can tangle and kill many dolphins. Awareness campaigns in the ‘80s led to a demand for “dolphin-safe tuna.”
While some truckers’ mudflaps depict a silhouette of a shapely woman, someone has in fact created a male version, showing a hunky guy in the same posture.
Commissioner James Gordon is Batman’s contact in the Gotham PD; on the ‘60s TV show he had a special flashing red phone to communicate with Batman.
An impression of Jackie Gleason’s hard-drinking character Reginald Van Gleason III, from The Jackie Gleason Show.
Psychologist Sigmund Freud theorized that adolescent girls pass through a stage of anxiety upon realizing they do not have a penis. He called this stage “penis envy.”
The sitcom Bosom Buddies starred a young Tom Hanks and Peter Scolari as two men who disguise themselves as women so they can live in a cheap women-only apartment building.
Lollapalooza is a hugely successful outdoor alt.-rock festival that toured the U.S. each summer from 1991-97. It was revived in 2003.
An imitation of the animated Canadian Mountie Dudley Do-Right. His damsel-in-distress in most episodes was Nell Fenwick.
Probably refers to a scene in the film The Abyss, where Ed Harris tries to resuscitate the drowned Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio by pounding on her chest and screaming at her.
The famous slogan of the De Beers diamond empire appeared in ads during the ‘80s & ‘90s: “How can you make two months’ salary last forever?”
A mixed bag of standard lines from the comedy shorts and films of The Three Stooges.
Mister Ed was a sitcom about a talking horse. The voice of Mister Ed (played by a palomino named Bamboo Harvester) was provided by former Western star Allan Lane.
Luciano Pavarotti is considered one of the finest tenors of the 20th century, and certainly the most commercially successful. He did not, however, dabble in the fine arts.
Good Seasons is a line of salad dressing mixes made by Kraft Foods.
Actor and writer Peter DeLuise is best known for playing Officer Doug Penhall on the TV show 21 Jump Street; he is the son of comedian Dom DeLuise.
If we somehow missed a reference, be sure to let us know in the comments.
May also be a reference to the comic book Fish Police, created by Steve Moncuse, which briefly became a TV show in 1992.
Cry Freedom is a film starring Denzel Washington and Kevin Klein, set during the apartheid era of South Africa.
A Dilly Bar is a disc of soft-serve ice cream coated in chocolate and served on a stick. It is still sold in Dairy Queens everywhere.
An imitation of Dean Martin and a reference to a singing and dancing group, The Dingaling Sisters, who performed on The Dean Martin Show.
A variation on Lauren Bacall’s classic line from To Have and Have Not: “You know how to whistle, don’t you, Steve? You just put your lips together and blow.”
Acapulco H.E.A.T. was a syndicated TV series about terrorism-fighting secret agents in Acapulco. It starred Catherine Oxenberg and Fabio’s chest.
Perkins Restaurant and Bakery is an American casual dining restaurant chain offering breakfast any time and selling fresh-baked pastries.
A Ramos Fizz—similar to a gin fizz—also contains orange flower water and egg whites, giving it a distinct flavor and texture.
Steak and Ale (named Jolly Ox in markets that didn’t allow references to booze in restaurant names) was a casual dining restaurant chain popular in the ‘80s.
The whippet is a very skinny breed of dog.
Buffy and Jody were two of the children on the sitcom Family Affair. (The third, a teenage girl, was named Cissy.)
Camaros are often thought of as the quintessential muscle car, although they are generally classified as a pony car.
Simon Says is an old kids’ game in which the “Simon” tells the other children to do things, prefacing each command with the words “Simon says.”
“The Impossible Dream (The Quest)” is a well-known song from the 1965 musical Man of La Mancha.
According to legend, in the film The Wizard of Oz, you can see a suicidal Munchkin hanging from a tree in the background in one scene. In fact it is a large bird spreading its wings.
“Hey, teen gang!” was a commonly heard exclamation in teen movies of the ‘50s and ‘60s. It became a catchphrase on MST3K.
Jeff Conaway (1950-2011) got his big break in the 1978 musical film Grease.
Episode 307, Daddy-O, featured Dick Contino as a crooning drag racer with a heart of gold and very high pants. The line “Want some?” featured prominently in one of the host segments.
A spin on Judy Garland’s famous line from The Wizard of Oz: “Toto, I’ve a feeling we’re not in Kansas anymore.”
In 1993, the Waco compound of the Branch Davidians was under siege by the government for 51 days until an FBI raid led to a massive fire and 76 deaths.
Judy Jetson was the teen daughter on the animated TV series The Jetsons. She sported a kicky pinkish-purple outfit with a short, puffy skirt.
In the Philippines in WWII, the Japanese marched about 70K Filipino & American POWs to a prison camp for days through the jungle. About 3K died on the Bataan Death March & 27K at the camp.
Chicken McNuggets are fried chicken bits served at McDonald’s fast food restaurants.
Macaroni is an Italian film about an uptight American businessman who learns to relax and enjoy life over the course of several days in Naples.
Hervé Villechaize, a little person French actor of part-Filipino descent, became famous for uttering the line “De plane! De plane!” on the TV show Fantasy Island.
The proverb “You can catch more flies with honey than with vinegar” dates back to a 1666 book of Italian proverbs, but it first appeared in the U.S. in Poor Richard’s Almanac by Ben Franklin.
A paraphrased line from the 1969 song “White Bird” by the psychedelic band It’s a Beautiful Day, off their self-titled debut album.
John Norman is a philosophy professor and author best known for the Gor novels; as of 2013 he had written 33. Outlaw of Gor was the second in the series.
Henry Fonda, one of the first major film stars to do American TV ads, was reportedly happy when his seven-year contract to plug GAF products ended.
“Shut up, Iris” is an oft-repeated line from Episode 415, The Beatniks.
In the movie Flashdance, Jennifer Beals wore an oversized sweatshirt with the collar cut off so it would slip off one shoulder; it created a brief but widespread fashion fad.
Iowa is a mid-sized state in the American Midwest. They grow a lot of corn and raise a lot of pigs. State nickname: “The Hawkeye State.”
Disgraced ballplayer Pete Rose has won three World Series rings. In 1989, Rose was permanently banned from baseball for betting on games while he played for and managed the Reds.
I-494 is an interstate loop and part of the beltway circling Minneapolis-St. Paul, Minnesota.
Barnaby Jones was a TV show starring Buddy “Jed Clampett” Ebsen as an elderly private eye.
Roxette is a Swedish pop-rock duo (one blond gal, one brunette dude) that enjoyed international success in the late ‘80s and early ‘90s.
Boba Fett is a rogue bounty hunter in the Star Wars films.
Levi’s 501 button-fly jeans were trendy from the mid-‘80s to the mid-‘90s.
According to the Bible, before Jesus’ crucifixion, he was offered up to be freed per Roman tradition, but the people chose another prisoner, Barabbas, instead.
A margarita is an alcoholic drink consisting of tequila mixed with orange liqueur and lime juice. It can be served on the rocks or blended, usually in a glass rimmed with salt.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
Servo also belts out Harry Alan Towers’ name in MST3K Episode 323, The Castle of Fu Manchu.
Known as “The Grey Lady,” The New York Times is a daily newspaper that has been continuously published in New York City since 1851.
Believed to be one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world, Jericho is a city near the banks of the Jordan River in the West Bank.
Pictionary is a board game in which teams of players try to guess words based on quick sketches made by their teammates.
Twins Matthew and Gunnar Nelson make up the core of the ‘90s rock band Nelson. They had very long blond hair.
The lambada is a Brazilian dance that became briefly popular in 1989. A film called The Forbidden Dance came out in 1990 in an attempt to capitalize on the fad.
An oft-repeated riff that was first heard, totally out of the blue and from an off-camera voice, in Episode 506, Eegah!
Miami Vice was a crime drama whose use of music and visual effects to tell a story was very influential on other TV shows in the late ‘80s.
The Red Onion is a famous restaurant in Aspen, Colorado. Established as a saloon in 1892, it is the oldest operating restaurant in that city.
Don’t Crush That Dwarf, Hand Me the Pliers is a 1970 album by comedy troupe The Firesign Theatre.
William Conrad was a portly actor known for such TV series as Cannon and Jake and the Fatman.
A paraphrase of a well-known saying by Eleanor Roosevelt: “Freedom makes a huge requirement of every human being. With freedom comes responsibility.”
Dr. Denton is a famous brand of blanket sleepers, also known as “footie pajamas.”
Palance often starred as the “heavy” in Westerns and as mob boss Carl Grissom in 1989’s Batman.
The legislature of Russia, the Federal Assembly, has two houses, the State Duma and the Federation Council, which meet in separate buildings in Moscow.
Tommy Tune is a ten-time Tony Award-winning dancer, choreographer, and theater director who’s also been known to sing and act.
It was not. Outlaw of Gor was a direct-to-video release on March 21, 1989.
Actor Eric Roberts, brother of actress Julia Roberts, is best known for Star 80, in which he played the sleazy husband of doomed Playmate Dorothy Stratten.
An imitation of actor Henry Fonda in a series of ads in the ‘70s for GAF Corporation’s flooring.
A reference to Episode 111, Moon Zero Two, a 1969 sci-fi film that was billed as the first “moon western.”
